Abstract = {{An increasing number of wireless intelligent equipment is applied to ICS
   networks. However, it is virtually impossible to use regular encryption
   methods and security patches to enhance the security level of legacy
   equipment in ICS networks due to weak computing and storage capabilities
   of the equipment. To address these concerns, a hybrid-augmented device
   fingerprinting approach is developed to enhance traditional intrusion
   detection mechanisms in the ICS network. Taking the advantage of the
   simplicity of the program process and stability of hardware
   configurations, we first measure inter-layer data response processing
   time, and then analyze network traffic to filter abnormal packets to
   achieve the intrusion classification and detection in ICS networks. The
   device finger-printing-based intrusion classification and detection
   approach is evaluated using the data collected from a lab-level
   micro-grid, and forgery attacks and intrusions are launched against the
   proposed method to investigate its robustness and effectiveness.}},
